<table-wrap xmlns:ali="http://www.niso.org/schemas/ali/1.0/" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" id="table1" position="float"><label>Table 1.</label><caption><title>Adult smoking prevalence (daily and non-daily) and daily cigarettes for US, UK, and Canada in 2000 and 2015.</title></caption><table frame="hsides" rules="groups"><thead><tr><th valign="top">Year</th><th valign="top">2000</th><th valign="top">2015</th><th valign="top">Change in %</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td colspan="4" valign="top"><bold>Prevalence*</bold></td></tr><tr><td valign="top">US</td><td valign="top">23.1</td><td valign="top">15.2</td><td valign="top">&#8722;34.2%</td></tr><tr><td valign="top">UK</td><td valign="top">27.0</td><td valign="top">17.8</td><td valign="top">&#8722;34.1%</td></tr><tr><td valign="top">Canada</td><td valign="top">24.4</td><td valign="top">13.0</td><td valign="top">&#8722;46.7%</td></tr><tr><td colspan="4" valign="top"><bold>Amount per day (among daily smokers)</bold></td></tr><tr><td valign="top">US</td><td valign="top">18.1</td><td valign="top">14.2</td><td valign="top">&#8722;21.5%</td></tr><tr><td valign="top">UK*</td><td valign="top">13.8</td><td valign="top">11.3</td><td valign="top">&#8722;18.1%</td></tr><tr><td valign="top">Canada</td><td valign="top">16.8</td><td valign="top">13.8</td><td valign="top">&#8722;17.9%</td></tr></tbody></table><table-wrap-foot><fn><p><sup>*</sup>Daily and non-daily smokers.</p><p><italic>Note.</italic> Data from National Centre for Health Statistics, <italic>NHIS;</italic> Office of National Statistics, <italic>Adult Smoking habits in Great Britain</italic>; Statistics Canada and <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bib103">Reid et al., 2017</xref>, <italic>Tobacco Use in Canada: Patterns and Trends, 2017 Edition</italic> &#8211;Defined as having smoked in the past 30 days and having smoked 100 cigarettes in a lifetime. Adult ages are 15+ in Canada and the UK and 18+ in the US.</p></fn></table-wrap-foot></table-wrap>